❌ Problem 1: class is not valid in JS
inpObj[i].class = 'inp';

This does nothing useful. In JavaScript you must use:

inpObj[i].className = 'inp';
// or (better)
inpObj[i].classList.add('inp');
⚠️ Problem 2: height mismatch
frameObj[i].style.height = '99%';
inpObj[i].style.height = '100%';

This can create subtle layout overflow issues depending on the parent element.
If you don’t have a specific reason, keep them consistent:

frameObj[i].style.height = '100%';
⚠️ Problem 3: performance (not critical but good to know)

Appending elements inside a loop like this:

container1.appendChild(frameObj[i]);

causes 69 DOM reflows.

A better pattern is to use a DocumentFragment:

const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();

for (let i = 0; i < 69; i++) {
    const frame = document.createElement('div');
    frame.style.width = '100%';
    frame.style.height = '100%';
    frame.style.border = '1px solid white';
    frame.id = 'frame' + i;

    const inp = document.createElement('textarea');
    inp.style.width = '100%';
    inp.style.height = '100%';
    inp.style.background = 'darkgreen';
    inp.style.color = 'white';
    inp.id = 'inp' + i;
    inp.classList.add('inp');
    inp.value = i;

    frame.appendChild(inp);
    fragment.appendChild(frame);
}

container1.appendChild(fragment);
⚠️ Problem 4: are arrays initialized?

Make sure you declared:

let frameObj = [];
let inpObj = [];

Otherwise you'll get unexpected behavior.

✔️ Summary
Fix class → use classList ✅
Consider DocumentFragment for efficiency ⚡
Watch your height settings 📏
Ensure arrays are initialized 🧠